.TH "FERRUM" "1" "2026-06-05" "Ferrum User Manual" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
ferrum - small Rust-native coding agent for Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] \f[B]-p\f[R] PROMPT OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] \f[B]\[en]resume\f[R] [REF] OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] \f[B]\[en]continue\f[R] OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] \f[B]\[en]session\f[R] REF OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]ferrum\f[R] \f[B]login\f[R] PROVIDER
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Ferrum is a Linux-native coding agent.
It provides interactive and one-shot prompt modes, local file and
guarded shell tools, model-facing session history lookup, image input,
JSONL sessions, AGENTS.md context loading, configurable providers,
OpenAI Codex / ChatGPT OAuth, OpenAI-compatible providers, Agent
Skills-style instructions, and a minimal MCP stdio bridge.
.PP
Ferrum stores sessions as JSONL files and restores context from previous
sessions when requested.
It is provider-neutral: providers translate messages to remote or local
model APIs, while Ferrum owns tools, sessions, context loading, and the
agent loop.
.SH MODES
.TP
\f[B]Interactive mode\f[R]
Run \f[B]ferrum\f[R] without \f[B]-p\f[R] to start an interactive
session.
.TP
\f[B]Print mode\f[R]
Use \f[B]-p\f[R], \f[B]\[en]print\f[R] to run one prompt and print the
answer.
.TP
\f[B]Resume mode\f[R]
Use \f[B]\[en]resume\f[R] to resume the latest session for the current
directory.
If no matching session exists, Ferrum starts a new session.
.TP
\f[B]Print-mode named session mode\f[R]
Use \f[B]\[en]session\f[R] REF with \f[B]-p\f[R] to resume or create a
named print-mode session.
If REF is a valid session id and no matching session exists, Ferrum
creates \f[B]REF.jsonl\f[R] in the session data directory.
.TP
\f[B]Interactive explicit session mode\f[R]
Use \f[B]\[en]session\f[R] REF or \f[B]\[en]resume\f[R] REF in
interactive mode to open an existing session by JSONL path or id prefix.
.TP
\f[B]Continue mode\f[R]
Use \f[B]\[en]continue\f[R] as an alias for continuing the latest
session for the current directory.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]-p\f[R], \f[B]\[en]print\f[R] PROMPT
Run a single prompt and print the answer.
If stdin is piped, Ferrum appends it to the prompt.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]provider\f[R] PROVIDER
Override the provider configured in config.toml.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]model\f[R] MODEL
Override the model configured in config.toml.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]thinking\f[R] LEVEL
Override thinking level.
Supported values are \f[B]off\f[R], \f[B]minimal\f[R], \f[B]low\f[R],
\f[B]medium\f[R], \f[B]high\f[R], and \f[B]xhigh\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\[en]safety\f[R] LEVEL
Override shell safety level for this process.
Supported values are \f[B]low\f[R], \f[B]medium\f[R], and
\f[B]high\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\[en]title\f[R] TITLE
Set the session title.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]image\f[R] PATH
Attach a local image file.
Repeatable.
Supported formats are png, jpg, jpeg, and webp.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]mcp\f[R] [SERVER \&...]
Enable configured MCP servers for this process.
If server names are provided, only those servers are enabled.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]no-mcp\f[R]
Disable MCP servers for this process.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]no-tools\f[R]
Disable all tools for this process.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]tools\f[R] TOOL \&...
Expose only the listed tools to the model.
.SH MODEL TOOLS
.PP
Ferrum\[cq]s default native tool set includes:
.PP
\f[B]read\f[R], \f[B]write\f[R], \f[B]edit\f[R], \f[B]bash\f[R],
\f[B]wait\f[R], \f[B]grep\f[R], \f[B]find\f[R], \f[B]ls\f[R],
\f[B]history_search\f[R], and \f[B]history_read\f[R].
.PP
The \f[V]bash\f[R] and \f[V]wait\f[R] tools apply a safety-tiered shell
guard before execution.
Use \f[B]\[en]safety low|medium|high\f[R] at startup or \f[B]/safety
low|medium|high\f[R] interactively to choose the trade-off.
The default \f[B]medium\f[R] tier rejects destructive patterns and
rewriteable opaque shell syntax while allowing common coding commands
such as Python one-liners and network tools.
.PP
The history tools are model-facing only.
They search or read the current session JSONL, including entries
archived before compaction, and return rendered text with JSONL line
numbers.
There is no slash command for these tools.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]resume\f[R] [REF]
Resume the latest session for the current directory, or resume a
specific session by JSONL path or id prefix.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]continue\f[R]
Continue the latest session for the current directory.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]session\f[R] REF
In print mode, resume or create a named session.
In interactive mode, open an existing session by JSONL path or id
prefix.
Valid named session ids use 1-80 characters from A-Z, a-z, 0-9, `.',
\[cq]_`, or'-`, and must not start with'.\[cq].
.TP
\f[B]-h\f[R], \f[B]\[en]help\f[R]
Print command help.
.TP
\f[B]-V\f[R], \f[B]\[en]version\f[R]
Print version.
.SH INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
.PP
Ferrum interactive mode supports slash commands and shell shortcuts.
.PP
Common slash commands:
.TP
\f[B]/help\f[R]
Show interactive help.
.TP
\f[B]/version\f[R]
Show Ferrum version.
.TP
\f[B]/session\f[R]
Show current session information.
.TP
\f[B]/sessions\f[R]
List recent sessions.
.TP
\f[B]/sessions pick\f[R]
Open an interactive session picker.
.TP
\f[B]/sessions del\f[R]
Open an interactive session deletion picker.
.TP
\f[B]/sessions new\f[R]
Start a new session.
.TP
\f[B]/title\f[R] TEXT
Set session title.
.TP
\f[B]/model\f[R] NAME
Switch model.
.TP
\f[B]/models\f[R]
List models known to the active provider.
.TP
\f[B]/provider\f[R] NAME
Switch provider.
.TP
\f[B]/providers\f[R]
List configured providers.
.TP
\f[B]/mcp\f[R] on|off|status|list
Manage MCP server availability for the current session.
.TP
\f[B]/thinking\f[R] LEVEL
Set thinking level.
.TP
\f[B]/safety\f[R] LEVEL
Set shell safety level.
.TP
\f[B]/diff\f[R] MODE
Set diff display mode.
.TP
\f[B]/colors\f[R] MODE
Set color mode.
.TP
\f[B]/palette\f[R] NAME
Show the current palette, or validate, apply, and persist a palette to
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/colors.toml\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]/palettes\f[R]
List palettes from \f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/color-palettes/\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]/usage\f[R] [day|week|month]
Show token usage summary.
.TP
\f[B]/skills\f[R]
List discovered skills.
.TP
\f[B]/skill\f[R] NAME [ARGS]
Load a skill.
.TP
\f[B]/skill:\f[R]NAME [ARGS]
Load a skill.
.TP
\f[B]/image\f[R] PATH
Attach an image.
.TP
\f[B]/image-paste\f[R]
Attach an image from the clipboard.
.TP
\f[B]/paste-image\f[R]
Attach an image from the clipboard.
.TP
\f[B]/compact\f[R]
Ask the model to compact session context.
.TP
\f[B]/quit\f[R], \f[B]/exit\f[R]
Exit Ferrum.
.PP
Shell shortcuts:
.TP
\f[B]!\f[R]COMMAND
Run a shell command and send its output to the model.
.TP
\f[B]!!\f[R]COMMAND
Run a shell command and show the output only to the user.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.PP
Ferrum reads configuration from:
.PP
\f[B]$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/ferrum/config.toml\f[R]
.PP
or, if XDG_CONFIG_HOME is unset:
.PP
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/config.toml\f[R]
.PP
A minimal OpenAI-compatible provider configuration looks like:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
provider = \[dq]local\[dq]
model = \[dq]local-model\[dq]

[providers.local]
type = \[dq]openai-compatible\[dq]
base_url = \[dq]http://localhost:8080\[dq]
default_model = \[dq]local-model\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Providers that require keys should use environment variables rather than
hardcoded secrets:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
[providers.example]
type = \[dq]openai-compatible\[dq]
base_url = \[dq]https://api.example.com/v1\[dq]
api_key_env = \[dq]EXAMPLE_API_KEY\[dq]
default_model = \[dq]example-model\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Ferrum supports a small semantic UI color palette.
Set the color mode in \f[B]config.toml\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
color = \[dq]auto\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Supported modes are \f[B]auto\f[R], \f[B]on\f[R], and \f[B]off\f[R].
Override palette entries in \f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/colors.toml\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
prompt = \[dq]DeepSkyBlue1\[dq]
tool = \[dq]bold LightSkyBlue3\[dq]
error = \[dq]OrangeRed1\[dq]
diff_added = \[dq]SpringGreen1\[dq]
diff_removed = \[dq]DeepPink1\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Supported color values include ANSI-style names such as \f[B]red\f[R],
\f[B]green\f[R], and \f[B]cyan\f[R], bright names such as
\f[B]bright-red\f[R], xterm 256-color table names such as
\f[B]Orange3\f[R] and \f[B]DeepSkyBlue1\f[R], styles such as
\f[B]bold\f[R] and \f[B]dim\f[R], RGB hex values such as
\f[B]#ffaa00\f[R], and xterm 256-color indexes such as \f[B]245\f[R].
Xterm names are matched case-insensitively.
Spaces, dashes, and underscores are ignored, and
\f[B]gray\f[R]/\f[B]grey\f[R] are equivalent.
Duplicate xterm names map to the first matching xterm index; use numeric
indexes for exact selection.
Reusable palettes can live in
**\[ti]/.config/ferrum/color-palettes/*.toml\f[B]; \f[R]/palette\f[B]
shows the current palette, \f[R]/palettes\f[B] lists palette files, and
\f[R]/palette NAME\f[B] validates and applies one live.
See \f[R]docs/colors.md** for all palette keys and color values.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/config.toml\f[R]
User configuration.
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/ferrum/colors.toml\f[R]
Optional semantic UI color palette.
.TP
**\[ti]/.config/ferrum/color-palettes/*.toml**
Optional reusable UI palettes selectable with \f[B]/palette\f[R] and
listed with \f[B]/palettes\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.local/share/ferrum/sessions/\f[R]
JSONL session store, unless data directory is overridden by XDG
variables.
.TP
\f[B]AGENTS.md\f[R]
Project and user instruction files loaded from the current directory
tree and configuration directory.
.SH INSTALLATION
.SS Release binary
.PP
Download the release tarball from Codeberg, extract it, and install the
binary and man page:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
curl -L https://codeberg.org/ominiverdi/ferrum/releases/download/v0.6.0/ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz | tar xz
sudo install -Dm755 ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/ferrum /usr/local/bin/ferrum
sudo install -Dm644 ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/docs/ferrum.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/ferrum.1
sudo mandb 2>/dev/null || true
ferrum --help
man ferrum
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Optional checksum verification:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
curl -LO https://codeberg.org/ominiverdi/ferrum/releases/download/v0.6.0/ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz
curl -LO https://codeberg.org/ominiverdi/ferrum/releases/download/v0.6.0/ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz.sha256
sha256sum -c ferrum-v0.6.0-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz.sha256
\f[R]
.fi
.SS From source
.PP
Install with Cargo:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
git clone https://codeberg.org/ominiverdi/ferrum.git
cd ferrum
cargo install --path .
ferrum --help
\f[R]
.fi
.SS System-wide man page
.PP
If a release tarball was extracted, the main install command above
installs the included man page.
From a source checkout, install \f[B]docs/ferrum.1\f[R] with:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sudo install -Dm644 docs/ferrum.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/ferrum.1
sudo mandb 2>/dev/null || true
man ferrum
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
If only \f[B]docs/ferrum.1.md\f[R] is present, generate the man page
with pandoc:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
pandoc -s -t man docs/ferrum.1.md -o docs/ferrum.1
\f[R]
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Run a one-shot prompt:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
ferrum -p \[dq]summarize this repo\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Pipe input into a prompt:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
cat src/main.rs | ferrum -p \[dq]review this file\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Use a local OpenAI-compatible provider:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
ferrum --provider local -p \[dq]say hello\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Resume the latest session for the current directory:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
ferrum --resume
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Attach an image:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
ferrum --image ./screenshot.png -p \[dq]describe this image\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Limit tool exposure:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
ferrum --tools read grep find -p \[dq]inspect this repo\[dq]
ferrum --no-tools -p \[dq]answer without tools\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
\f[B]cargo\f[R](1), \f[B]git\f[R](1), \f[B]pandoc\f[R](1)
.PP
Project repository: https://codeberg.org/ominiverdi/ferrum
